		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Molecular gastronomy</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:302px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Raw_egg.jpg" class="image" title="A classic example of molecular gastronomy is the investigation of the effect of specific temperatures on the yolk and white when cooking an egg. Many cookbooks provide the instructions of boiling eggs 3-6 minutes for soft yolks, 6-8 minutes for a medium yolk and so on. Molecular gastronomy reveals that the amount of time is less important to cooking the eggs than specific temperatures - which always yields the desired result.[1][2]"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/Raw_egg.jpg/300px-Raw_egg.jpg" width="300" height="209" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Raw_egg.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
A classic example of molecular gastronomy is the investigation of the effect of specific temperatures on the yolk and white when cooking an egg. Many cookbooks provide the instructions of boiling eggs 3-6 minutes for soft yolks, 6-8 minutes for a medium yolk and so on. Molecular gastronomy reveals that the amount of time is less important to cooking the eggs than specific temperatures - which always yields the desired result.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Molecular gastronomy</b> is a scientific discipline involving the study of physical and chemical processes that occur in cooking.<sup id="cite_ref-autogenerated12_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-autogenerated12-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup> It pertains to the mechanisms behind the transformation of ingredients in cooking and the social, artistic and technical components of <a href="/wiki/Culinary" title="Culinary" class="mw-redirect">culinary</a> and <a href="/wiki/Gastronomic" title="Gastronomic" class="mw-redirect">gastronomic</a> phenomena in general (from a scientific point of view).</p>
